"There is no shame when you value your life this way," says former police informant Fatoumata Sono Maïga, who pulled Sounkalo from a taxi and took her to an underground abortionist, who delivered the still-deformed child by the roadside.

Sounkalo would later lie to the police about the transfer of the dead baby's body and attempt to prevent police from gaining access to the abortionist's premises, the RSF reported.

Under Mali's current law, abortion is permitted only in cases of rape, to preserve the life of the mother, or in the case of an ectopic pregnancy. Abortion is considered "extraordinary," and under sections 207 and 220 of the criminal code, a doctor who performs an illegal abortion can face up to 10 years in jail and a fine of between 100,000 and 3.5 million CFA francs (about $180 to $6,400), according to Doctors Without Borders.

However, since 1977, when the National Assembly of Mali enacted an amnesty allowing women and men to go to court for abortion-related charges from between 1956 and 1976 and pleaded for impunity for the procedure, the legal restrictions on abortion have not been widely applied.
